{{Infobox language |name=Bauwaki |nativename= |region=[[Papua New Guinea]] |speakers=520 |date=2000 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Papuan |fam1=[[Trans–New Guinea languages|Trans–New Guinea]] |fam2=[[Papuan Peninsula languages|Papuan Peninsula]] |fam3=Owen Stanley Range<ref>[https://sites.google.com/site/newguineaworld/families/trans-new-guinea/papuan-peninsula/owen-stanley-range New Guinea World, Owen Stanley Range]</ref> |fam4=Mailu–Yereban |iso3=bwk |glotto=bauw1241 |glottorefname=Bauwaki–Ooku }}
'''Bauwaki''' (Bawaki) is a [[Papuan language]] of New Guinea, sometimes classified as a member of the [[Mailuan languages|Mailuan]] family. It is 70% lexically similar to [[Abia language|Abia]] of the [[Yareban languages|Yareban]] family. Dutton (1971) proposed it to be a 'bridge' between the [[Mailuan languages|Mailuan]] and Yareban language families.<ref name=e18 /> O'oku, either a dialect or a closely related language, is similarly lexically 60% Yareban.
