{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}
{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}
The history of [[Bible translations]] into the [[Konkani language]] begins with Ignazio Arcamone (1615–1683), an Italian Jesuit working in Salcette, [[Goa]] was the first to translate parts of the Bible to [[Konkani language]].<ref name="mangalorean.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.mangalorean.com/news.php?newstype=local&newsid=29346|title=Mangalorean.com - Mangalore News Articles, Classifieds to Around the World|publisher=Mangalorean.com|accessdate=7 December 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209070936/http://www.mangalorean.com/news.php?newstype=local&newsid=29346|archivedate=9 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was published under the title "Sogllea Vorunsache Vanjel" from Rachol Seminary Printing Press in 1667. Copies of this book are not available. 

The New Testament was translated into Konkani in Latin script in 1818.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldscriptures.org/pages/konkanigoan.html|title=The Bible in Konkani: Goan|publisher=Worldscriptures.org|accessdate=7 December 2014}}</ref> The complete New Testament was first translated into Konkani in [[Kannada]] script by William Robert Da Silva in 1977. With the publication of Baibol in 1997, he became the first person to translate the complete Bible into Konkani.<ref name="mangalorean.com"/> He translated it single-handedly over 30 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goa-world.com/goa/books/bible.htm |accessdate=5 April 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322204244/http://www.goa-world.com/goa/books/bible.htm |archivedate=22 March 2012 }}</ref> The second complete translation was done by William B. Barboza in 2000 titled Pavitr Pustak.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cathnewsindia.com/2009/07/30/konkani-bible-website-launched/ |title=Cath Legal News |publisher=Cathnewsindia.com |accessdate=7 December 2014 }}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Both these were printed in Kannada script. The third complete translation was edited by Manuel Gomes in 2006 titled Povitr Pustok.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.oneindia.in/2006/06/05/first-konkani-version-of-bible-in-roman-script-released-1149491699.html|title=First Konkani version of Bible in Roman script released|work=www.oneindia.com|accessdate=7 December 2014}}</ref> It was printed in [[Latin script]]. Others who translated parts of the Bible into Konkani are [[William Carey (missionary)|William Carey]] at Serampore, [[West Bengal]]; Joaquim A. Fernandes, Mumbai; Rymond Mascarenhas, Mangalore; Sylvester Menezes, Mangalore; C.C.A. Pai,  S.J., Mangalore; [[Fr. Vasco do Rego SJ]], Goa; [[Moreno de Souza]], S.J., Goa; and Felicio Cardozo, Goa<ref name="mangalorean.com"/>

