{{Infobox language |name=Mag-Indi |nativename=''Mag-indi'' |states=[[Philippines]] |region=[[Floridablanca, Pampanga|Floridablanca]], [[Porac, Pampanga|Porac]], [[San Marcelino, Zambales|San Marcelino]] |ethnicity=30,000 (no date)<ref name=e17>{{e17|blx}}</ref> |speakers=5,000 |date=1998 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3=[[Philippine languages|Philippine]] |fam4=[[Central Luzon languages|Central Luzon]] |fam5=[[Sambalic languages|Sambalic]] |iso3=blx |glotto=magi1241 |glottorefname=Mag-Indi Ayta }}
The '''Indi language''', '''''Mag-indi''''' (or Mag-Indi Ayta) is a [[Sambalic language]] with around 5,000 speakers.<ref name=e18/> It is spoken within Philippine [[Aeta]] communities in [[San Marcelino, Zambales]], and in the [[Pampanga|Pampango]] municipalities of [[Floridablanca, Pampanga|Floridablanca]] (including in Nabuklod<ref>http://www-01.sil.org/asia/philippines/splc/SPLC19-10_Stone.pdf</ref>) and [[Porac, Pampanga|Porac]]. There are also speakers in Lumibao and Maague-ague.<ref name="Himes2012">Himes, Ronald S. 2012. “[https://www.jstor.org/stable/23321866 The Central Luzon Group of Languages]”. ''Oceanic Linguistics'' 51 (2). University of Hawai'i Press: 490–537.</ref>
